 for Spinozism of late by those who see his work as a kind of neo-vitalism or philosophy of life and affect. Peden counters this trend by tracking a decisive and neglected aspect of Spinoza's philosophy-his rationalism-in a body of thought too often presumed to have rejected reason. In the process, he demonstrates that the virtues of Spinoza's rationalism have yet to be exhausted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchx20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 0aRationalism. 4aAlthusser. 4aDeleuze. 4aFrench intellectual history. 4aSpinoza. 4aSpinozism. 4aontology. 4aphenomenology. 4arationalism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479136640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791366423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791366.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles